  "chunk_index": 17,
  "summary": "From her hiding place in the wardrobe, Bondel observes a secret meeting of individuals wearing hourglass masks. The host is the bearded Russian, Mr. Mosgolovsky. Other attendees include an American with an Irish accent identified as \"four o'clock,\" an elegant, tall man known as \"five o'clock,\" a beautiful woman of Slavic appearance, and a person with a well-bred British accent identified as \"three o'clock.\" The group discusses the absence of \"two o'clock\" and the mysterious \"seven o'clock,\" a leader who called the meeting but has never been seen.\n\nThe members express concern regarding potential danger and the risk of someone discovering their location and the \"chimney house.\" Mosgolovsky emphasizes the necessity of silencing suspicious individuals. The conversation shifts to business involving a \"two-footed dragon church\" and a guest list featuring Sir Stanley Digby and Countess Anna Razky. They also discuss the significant commercial and international value of an invention created by Herr Eberhard.\n\nThe meeting reveals that a letter from Gerry Wade mentioning their organization was discovered by Miss Irene Brent, a failure attributed to someone named Bourne. Additionally, the members confirm they have successfully covered up the death of Ronnie De Vere by making it appear to be an accident involving a local boy. After the meeting concludes with a salute to \"Anna,\" the members depart through a hidden door. Two hours later, Alfred arrives to release a pale and anxious Bondel from the wardrobe.",
